\section*{Objectives}
t By the end of the lecture, the student should be able to:
Ø Define Histology

Ø Outline the various stages of preparing slides.

Ø Scientific basis of the various stages of preparing slides.

\section*{What is Histology.}
t Is the scientific study of the fine details of cells and tissues using a microscope to look at specimens of tissue that have been carefully prepared using special techniques called Histological techniques.
t Is Greek word -"histos= tissue" and "logos=study".
t Histopathology: microscopic examination of biological tissues to observe the appearance of diseased cells and tissues in very fine details.
t Histo-chemistry: study of the identification and distribution of chemical compounds within and between biological cells using histological techniques such as staining, indicators and light.

\section*{Uses of histology}
t Education- in teaching abs to help students appreciate the microstructures of biological tissues.
t Diagnosis - to inform treatment options
t Research
t Forensic investigations (Autopsy)- to determine possible causes of sudden death.
t Archeology - for tissues recovered from archeological sites ie bone and teeth, provide insights into history and past events

\section*{Steps in slide preparation}
t Tissue collection and preparation
t Fixation
t Processing
t Embedding
t Sectioning
t Staining
t Mounting
t Microscopy.

\section*{Sample preparation}
t Tissues are obtained from closest relatives of man= olive baboon
t 3 months Quarantine = observation for zoonoses
t Darting/anaesthesia
t Perfusion- washing with normal saline and introducing a fixative(mainly formaldehyde) through the carotid artery.
t Immersing the animal in 10\% formal saline.
t Purpose of fixation:
ü Preserve the tissue in a life-like manner as possible
ü Kills the tissue to avoid postmortem changes= autolysis and putrefaction
ü Cross-linking thus adding strength to the tissue

\section*{Cont'd}
t Tissues are obtained in cubes of 1 cm , some times less
t Larger tissues do not fix well as the fixative and embedding media do not penetrate to all the sections.
t Trim wit a sharp blade to obtain regular and fine edges
t Put tissues in specimen bottles and label them ready for processing

