\section*{Hepatic cell types}
- Hepatocytes
- Predominant cell type in the liver.
${ }^{\circ}$ An estimated $80 \%$ of the liver mass is made of these cells.
- The hepatocytes are round in shape containing a nucleus and an abundance of cellular organelles associated with metabolic and secretory functions.
- Ultrastructure? Relate to functions?
- Hepatic stellate cells (of Ito)
- Lie within the space of Disse.
- Stellate cells store vitamin A in characteristic lipid droplets.
- In addition, many stellate cells in the normal liver express alpha-smooth muscle actin.
- In chronic liver injury, the stellate cell differentiates into a myofibroblast-like cell
- Kupffer cells
critical component of the mononuclear phagocytic system and are central to both the hepatic and systemic response to pathogens.
- Capillary endothelial cells
- The discontinuous sinusoidal endothelium has a discontinuous basal lamina that is absent over large areas.
- The discontinuity of the endothelium is evident in two ways:
- Large fenestrae, without diaphragms, are present within the endothelial cells
- Large gaps are present between neighboring endothelial cells.
